      <div class="en-block">
        <p>Becoming a surgical oncologist in India requires: MBBS (5.5 years), MS General Surgery (3 years), M.Ch Surgical Oncology (3 years). That is 11+ years of dedicated training. A general surgeon can operate on cancer. But cancer-specific decisions require dedicated training.</p>
        <p>What I mean is: oncological margins, extent of lymph node dissection, whether multi-organ resection is needed, reconstruction choices, neoadjuvant vs adjuvant therapy timing — all of these are decisions that need cancer-specific knowledge. Published literature consistently shows better outcomes at specialised surgical oncology centres.</p>
        <p>My specific training: AIIMS M.Ch (GI cancers thesis), Hannover ESSO Fellowship (peritoneal surface malignancy), Charité Berlin (advanced GI techniques), FEBS and FACS. This combination is rare in Hyderabad.</p>
